T1  - Understanding Organizational Change: A Schematic Perspective
AU  - Lau, Chung-Ming
AU  - Woodman, Richard W.
Y1  - 1995/04/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256692
DO  - 10.5465/256692
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 537
EP  - 554
VL  - 38
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The construct of change schema is developed and its possible dimensions explained. Using data from two samples and both quantitative and qualitative methods, we found that locus of control and organizational commitment were related to specific dimensions of the construct. Dogmatism was not related in the specific manner hypothesized. Further, the hypothesized role of change schema as a mediator between these individual differences, general attitude toward change, and attitudes toward specific changes was generally supported.
AB  - The construct of change schema is developed and its possible dimensions explained. Using data from two samples and both quantitative and qualitative methods, we found that locus of control and organizational commitment were related to specific dimensions of the construct. Dogmatism was not related in the specific manner hypothesized. Further, the hypothesized role of change schema as a mediator between these individual differences, general attitude toward change, and attitudes toward specific changes was generally supported.
